---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import ToolReview from '../../components/ToolReview.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';
const path = '/alternatives/brevo-alternative';
const title = 'Best Brevo Alternatives for Shopify (2026)';
const desc = 'Why Shopify merchants leave Brevo — automation ceiling, thin Shopify segmentation, outgrown pay-per-email savings — plus eight ranked alternatives and migration checklist.';

const altSlugs = ['sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'omnisend', 'drip', 'mailchimp', 'activecampaign', 'sendlane', 'shopify-email'];
const alternatives = altSlugs.map((s) => appBySlug(s)!);

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Why do Shopify stores leave Brevo?',
    answer: 'Brevo wins early on price — then loses when merchants need Shopify-native browse abandonment, replenishment by product type, and winback logic Brevo templates do not express. Pay-per-email savings erode when teams compensate for weak automation by sending more broadcasts to hit revenue targets, or when they hire agencies to wire workarounds Brevo was supposed to replace.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is Sequenzy better than Brevo for Shopify lifecycle?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy replaces Brevo when strategy speed matters more than raw send volume pricing. Agent-first playbooks build welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and winback without Brevo\'s template ceiling. Pay-per-email economics are comparable — the upgrade is lifecycle depth and decision support, not necessarily lower bills.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I export Brevo automations?',
    answer: 'Automations do not transfer natively. Export workflow screenshots and contact lists with attributes. Rebuild in the new platform using Shopify sync rather than static CSV segments where possible. Migration is a chance to delete zombie automations Brevo let you keep running cheaply.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How long does Brevo migration take?',
    answer: 'Plan 2–3 weeks for disciplined Shopify lifecycle migration: week one exports and rebuilds welcome plus cart, week two parallel suppression, week three winback and replenishment. Brevo\'s simpler automation library migrates faster than Klaviyo — unless you built complex custom workflows on top of basic tooling.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I stay on Brevo and add a second tool?',
    answer: 'Some stores keep Brevo for transactional email and move marketing lifecycle to Sequenzy or Klaviyo. Dual ESP adds deliverability complexity — prefer one marketing platform connected to Shopify if possible. Split stacks work when Brevo handles order confirmations and a dedicated tool owns retention.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which Brevo alternative is best for SMS?',
    answer: 'Omnisend bundles email, SMS, and push with simpler onboarding than Brevo SMS add-ons. Postscript or Attentive win for SMS-first strategies. Do not run Brevo SMS and new platform SMS in parallel — TCPA overlap risk.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is Klaviyo worth the upgrade from Brevo?',
    answer: 'When catalog complexity and predictive segmentation drive revenue — variant back-in-stock, collection browse, CLV-based winback — Klaviyo justifies profile pricing. When Brevo pain is "we need better welcome and cart," Sequenzy or Omnisend deliver faster ROI than Klaviyo\'s learning curve.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What happens to Brevo contact attributes on migration?',
    answer: 'Export custom attributes and list membership with consent timestamps. Map purchase recency and product interest to dynamic Shopify segments in the new platform. Static Brevo lists go stale — dynamic segments stay accurate as catalog changes.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should I stay on Brevo?',
    answer: 'Stay when send volume is predictable, automation needs are modest, and pay-per-email economics still beat alternatives after honest send modeling. Brevo remains excellent for budget-conscious brands not yet past 500 orders/month lifecycle complexity.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/alternatives">Alternatives</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-cyan-100/90">/</span>
        <span class="text-cyan-100/90">Brevo alternatives</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="badge">Graduation moment</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Best Brevo alternatives for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-cyan-100">
          Brevo is where smart Shopify merchants start — pay-per-email pricing, dependable deliverability, no profile bill shock. The exit arrives when "affordable" becomes "insufficient." Browse abandonment that cannot branch by collection. Winback that is a single template. Post-purchase that never cross-sells by category. You saved $200/month on Klaviyo and spent it on manual campaign labor instead.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-cyan-100/90">
          This guide is for stores outgrowing Brevo's automation ceiling, not stores Brevo still fits. Sequenzy ranks first when lifecycle strategy is the bottleneck. Klaviyo ranks when predictive Shopify data is. See <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-omnisend">Brevo vs Omnisend</a> if you are torn between two mid-tier upgrades.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          title="Top Brevo replacements for Shopify"
          picks={[
            { label: 'Best overall upgrade', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Agent-first lifecycle playbooks when Brevo templates hit their ceiling — comparable pay-per-email economics with strategy built in.' },
            { label: 'Best Shopify data platform', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'Predictive segmentation and catalog-native triggers when Brevo\'s Shopify sync was always "good enough" until it wasn\'t.' },
            { label: 'Best fast multichannel', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Prebuilt journeys with SMS and push when Brevo email worked but channel expansion stalled.' },
            { label: 'Best workflow builder', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Visual automation for operators who want Brevo\'s price discipline with more branching control.' },
            { label: 'Best familiar editor', tool: 'Mailchimp', reason: 'Lateral move when Brevo UX frustrated — rarely the upgrade path, but some teams prefer it.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why Shopify merchants leave Brevo</h2>
        <p>
          The automation ceiling is the headline. A beauty brand runs Brevo successfully through year one — welcome, cart, monthly newsletter. Year two demands replenishment by serum vs moisturizer, winback before seasonal clearance, VIP early access without training discount hunters. Brevo's automation builder can approximate some of this with tags and manual lists, but maintenance becomes weekly list exports the platform was supposed to eliminate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Shopify segmentation depth is the second fracture. Collection-level browse abandonment, variant back-in-stock, suppressing recent full-price buyers during sales — Brevo syncs orders but merchandising intelligence trails Klaviyo, Omnisend, and Sequenzy. Operators compensate with broadcast blasts, which defeats pay-per-email savings and hurts deliverability when engagement drops.
        </p>
        <p>
          Transactional plus marketing confusion triggers some exits. Brevo handles order confirmations well; marketing automation feels like a different product wearing the same login. Teams split stacks or migrate marketing entirely rather than fight unified contact models that mix transactional recipients with lifecycle segments incorrectly.
        </p>
        <p>
          Brevo is not a mistake for early-stage DTC. It is a graduation point. If your honest assessment is two flows and a newsletter, stay and save money. If you are hiring retention help because Brevo cannot express your playbook, the alternatives below are the correct next chapter — not a betrayal of frugal instincts.
        </p>

        <h2>Brevo migration checklist for Shopify</h2>
        <p>Run this before disconnecting Brevo marketing automations from Shopify. Transactional email can remain on Brevo temporarily if you split stacks deliberately.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Separate transactional from marketing.</strong> Document which Brevo templates handle orders vs lifecycle. Decide single-platform or split-stack strategy before migration.</li>
          <li><strong>Export consent records.</strong> CSV with email, SMS status, consent timestamp, and signup source. Required for compliant list import.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit active automations.</strong> List every workflow with last enrollment date. Disable zombies still sending to unengaged contacts.</li>
          <li><strong>Export contact attributes.</strong> Custom fields, list membership, purchase tags. Document attribute definitions for rebuild.</li>
          <li><strong>Connect new platform to Shopify first.</strong> Verify product catalog, order history, and customer sync before bulk import.</li>
          <li><strong>Rebuild welcome and cart.</strong> Test with real Shopify test orders. Pause Brevo equivalents only after new flows pass.</li>
          <li><strong>Run parallel suppression 14 days.</strong> Tag migrated customers. No duplicate cart recovery from Brevo and new platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Add post-purchase, winback, replenishment.</strong> The flows that triggered Brevo graduation — build with simpler logic than Brevo workarounds required.</li>
          <li><strong>Redirect signup forms.</strong> Update Privy, popups, and checkout integrations to feed new platform lists.</li>
          <li><strong>Warm sending domain if ESP changes.</strong> Ramp marketing volume over 7–14 days. See <a class="link" href="/use-cases/deliverability">deliverability guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>Downgrade Brevo marketing tier.</strong> Keep transactional-only plan if splitting stacks.</li>
          <li><strong>Archive Brevo campaigns 90 days.</strong> Historical reference before canceling marketing features.</li>
        </ol>
      </article>

      <section class="container space-y-12 py-16">
        <p class="badge">Ranked alternatives</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-white">Eight Brevo alternatives for Shopify stores</h2>

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[0]}
          rank={1}
          badge="Top pick"
          paragraphs={[
            'Sequenzy is the Brevo upgrade we recommend when price was never the only requirement — capability was. Brevo kept bills low; Sequenzy adds lifecycle strategy defaults Brevo lacks: replenishment by product type, seasonal winback with suppression rules, education-first post-purchase. Agent-first setup describes outcomes instead of forcing you to invent automation architecture on a budget platform.',
            'Pay-per-email pricing parallels Brevo\'s model — you are not jumping to profile-based sticker shock unless you choose Klaviyo. The migration payoff is operational: fewer manual list exports, fewer broadcast band-aids compensating for weak automation, clearer playbook for whoever edits copy Thursday night.',
            'Sequenzy will not replicate Brevo\'s transactional email strength in one login — split stacks remain valid. Read <a class="link" href="/compare/privy-vs-brevo">Privy vs Brevo</a> if capture tooling completes your stack review.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[1]}
          rank={2}
          paragraphs={[
            'Klaviyo is the Brevo graduation when Shopify data depth drives margin — not when you merely want prettier templates. Predictive CLV, collection browse abandonment, variant triggers, and holdout testing justify profile pricing for catalogs over 500 SKUs with seasonal complexity.',
            'Brevo migrants often underestimate Klaviyo operational overhead. You trade automation ceiling for segmentation discipline — budget time for weekly segment audits or hire help. Compare <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-omnisend">Brevo vs Omnisend</a> if Klaviyo feels like overkill.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[2]}
          rank={3}
          paragraphs={[
            'Omnisend is the fastest Brevo exit for multichannel expansion. Prebuilt welcome, cart, and post-purchase with email, SMS, and push install in days — deeper than Brevo without Klaviyo\'s learning curve. Contact pricing behaves similarly to Brevo at small scale with bundled channel value.',
            'Choose Omnisend when Brevo email worked but SMS and push were add-on friction. Many merchants run Omnisend 12–18 months after leaving Brevo, then reassess against Klaviyo or Sequenzy.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[3]}
          rank={4}
          paragraphs={[
            'Drip appeals to Brevo users who started building custom workflows and hit the builder ceiling. Visual automation supports collection browse and winback branching with clearer UX than Brevo\'s automation tab — at per-contact pricing that may exceed Brevo send costs.',
            'Pick Drip if someone enjoys hands-on workflow design and your catalog is focused. Not the budget choice — the control choice after Brevo simplicity became constraint.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[4]}
          rank={5}
          paragraphs={[
            'Mailchimp is the lateral move when Brevo UX frustrated your team — familiar editor, similar mid-tier capability, rarely a true upgrade for Shopify lifecycle. Some agencies default to Mailchimp; DTC retention stores outgrow both on similar timelines.',
            'Choose Mailchimp only if stakeholder familiarity outweighs Shopify-native depth. Budget another migration if lifecycle becomes strategic priority.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[5]}
          rank={6}
          paragraphs={[
            'ActiveCampaign is the Brevo alternative when CRM pipelines overlap ecommerce — wholesale inquiries, high-ticket follow-up, sales-assigned nurture. Conditional branching exceeds Brevo for sales workflows; Shopify catalog depth trails Klaviyo.',
            'Choose ActiveCampaign when leaving Brevo because retention and sales ops must share one database — not when you only need better cart recovery.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[6]}
          rank={7}
          paragraphs={[
            'Sendlane fits Brevo graduates ready to invest in guided retention — onboarding support, deliverability consultation, ecommerce-first templates. Higher entry price assumes order volume justifies white-glove migration from Brevo workarounds.',
            'Sendlane wins when Brevo ceiling was operational, not financial, and you will pay to rebuild correctly once.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[7]}
          rank={8}
          paragraphs={[
            'Shopify Email is the downgrade path when Brevo graduation was aspirational — you realize lifecycle ambitions paused and sale blasts suffice. No automation depth, no SMS.',
            'Useful as 90-day reset during cash conservation. Stores that left Brevo for capability reasons rarely stay on Shopify Email long if revenue goals remain.',
            'Treat as pause button, not Brevo replacement for growth-focused DTC.',
          ]}
        />
      </section>

      <div class="container mb-12 max-w-4xl card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-white">Pricing comparison vs Brevo</h2>
        <p class="px-5 pb-4 text-cyan-100/90">Illustrative monthly costs — Brevo savings shrink when send volume rises or platforms bill by contacts.</p>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Platform</th><th>~10k contacts</th><th>~25k contacts</th><th>~50k contacts</th><th>Billing model</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Brevo (leaving)</td><td>$25–65</td><td>$50–120</td><td>$100–200</td><td>Email volume</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sequenzy</td><td>$19–79</td><td>$49–149</td><td>$99–249</td><td>Pay per email sent</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Klaviyo</td><td>$150–200</td><td>$350–450</td><td>$600–900+</td><td>Active profiles + SMS</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Omnisend</td><td>$60–100</td><td>$120–180</td><td>$200–350</td><td>Contacts + volume</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Drip</td><td>$80–120</td><td>$150–250</td><td>$280–450</td><td>People in account</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Mailchimp</td><td>$50–100</td><td>$100–200</td><td>$200–350</td><td>Contacts + sends</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="container max-w-4xl pb-8 text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-white">Related guides</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/apps/brevo">Brevo review</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-omnisend">Brevo vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-mailchimp">Brevo vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/postscript-vs-brevo">Postscript vs Brevo</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/alternatives">All alternatives</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-12">
      <h2>TCPA, consent, and cost-per-message discipline</h2>
      <p>SMS on Shopify is not a faster email channel. Every send needs express written consent, documented opt-in source, quiet-hour configuration, and a margin model that includes platform fees, carrier surcharges, and discount depth. Postscript, Attentive, and Omnisend SMS expose compliance tooling — but merchants still own consent copy at checkout, popups, and keyword campaigns.</p>
      <p>Model cost per delivered message before scaling broadcasts. A recovered cart that required 25% off plus three texts is often negative contribution margin even when attribution dashboards look green. Pair urgent SMS with Sequenzy email when the message needs education, social proof, or multi-product context — never duplicate the same offer on both channels within twenty-four hours unless the subscriber opted into high-frequency updates.</p>
      <p>Weekly ops: audit STOP/HELP handling, reply inbox backlog, opt-out spikes by flow, and suppression overlap with email cart recovery. Quarterly: re-read popup and checkout consent language against live automations. TCPA litigation and carrier filtering both punish stores that treat SMS like promotional email with shorter copy.</p>
    </div>



  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Brevo alternatives FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
